				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: &amp;quot;Bards are only good for DPS and Haste&amp;quot;<a name="55875"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Aug 10 04 10:43 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>At least he didn't come back and train your friends for the threat of kicking him out of the group.
<br />

<br />
If I have the misfortune of becoming grouped with such a person, I find a way to make the situation work minus that persons involvment. Your friends had at least a cleric, right? Or if not, they had a necro. Necros get undead lulls, and clerics have enchanter comparable lulls. Necro could have pulled the undeads and the cleric could have taken over for the non-undead. There was no real reason to rely on a bard, especially a poor one.
<br />

<br />
No cleric? Necro pet could pull singles all day with enough spamming of /pet backoff. Make sure he doesnt sit, FD helps.
<br />

<br />
I am not trying to put down your friends. Only that in situations where one person performs poorly, you can often find a way to compensate. I've had bards that refused to pull when I played my cleric. I never thought twice about it, I'll pull myself. Or on my monk alt, I'd much rather pull than a bard that is only half-convinced of doing the job.
<br />

<br />
At lvl 65, on a normal, I found that we could almost work with no healer and me on slows. Our cleric goes LD along with our BL. That left me, a warrior, a rogue and a necro. Twisting marr and nivs I could keep the warrior at 100% hps while pulling singles and preslowing, it was quite surprising. Think I was doing about 110 pts/tick and the necro applied his hot on top of that.</span></td>
